AUDIO: 'you might have seen AI tools that animate human photos using reference videos but what about cartoons animals or even madeup creatures well there\'s a new player in town that changes everything animate X developed by ant group and Alibaba this open- Source tool'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lets you animate non-human characters with ease and it\'s about to redefine how we approach animation let\'s dive in and see how it works anime Tex is specifically designed'

[00:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to animate cartoon characters animals and other non-human creatures previously most open-source AI tools like mimic motion only worked well for animating humans you could take a reference photo'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of a person and map it onto a pose video allowing the human character to move but when it came to non-human characters like cartoons or creatures with weird limbs those tools just didn\'t cut it animate X solves this'

[00:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'challenge so how does animate X work it\'s a simple simp but powerful process first you start with two inputs a reference image and a reference video the reference image is the character you'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want to animate and the reference video defines the movements you want to map onto that character the reference video can be of anyone someone dancing a person moving or even you acting out the movement next the reference video is'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'converted into a pose video which is basically a skeleton model of the movement in the video this POS video is then processed in two different ways the first is through what\'s called the implicit pose indicator or IPI this step'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tells the system how the character should move focusing on overall motion the second step is the explicit pose indicator which refines the character specific poses once these two steps are'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'done both sets of data are combined with your original reference image and the whole system goes through a diffusion model this model generates the frames for the final video bringing your character to Life In Motion let\'s take a'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
